<section xml:id="AD5" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Derivative tests (AD5) </title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <xi:include href="outcomes/05.ptx" />
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <activity xml:id="activity-derivative-derivativetests1">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Let <m>f</m> be a function defined on some interval <m>(a,b)</m>. Let <m>x_1</m> and <m>x_2</m> be two points in the interval such that <m>x_1 &lt; x_2 </m>.  
      </p>
    </introduction>
      <task>
      <statement>
          <p>What can we say about the graph of the function on <m>(a,b)</m> if <m>f(x_1)</m> is always less than <m>f(x_2)</m> on <m>(a,b)</m>?</p>
          <ol label="A">
              <li><p>The function is decreasing on <m>(a,b)</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>The function is increasing on <m>(a,b)</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>The function is constant on <m>(a,b)</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>The function could be some combination of increasing, decreasing, and/or constant on <m>(a,b)</m></p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
      </task>
  </activity>

      <activity xml:id="activity-derivative-derivativetests2">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Sketch a graph of a continuous function that is increasing on <m>(-\infty, -2)</m> and constant on <m>(3,5)</m> and decreasing on <m>(-2,1)</m>.  
      </p>
    </introduction>
      <task>
      <statement>
          <p>How would you describe the derivative of the function on each interval?</p>
          <ol label="A">
              <li><p><m>f'(x) &lt; 0</m> on <m>(-2,1)</m> and <m>(3,5)</m> and <m>f'(x) &gt; 0</m> on <m>(-2,1)</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p> <m>f'(x) &gt; 0</m> on <m>(-2,1)</m>, <m>f'(x) &lt; 0</m> on <m>(-2,1)</m> and <m>f'(x)</m> is undefined on <m>(3,5)</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p><m>f'(x) &gt; 0</m> on <m>(-2,1)</m>, <m>f'(x) &lt; 0</m> on <m>(-2,1)</m> and <m>f'(x) = 0</m> on <m>(3,5)</m>. </p></li>
              <li><p><m>f'(x) &gt; 0</m> on <m>(-2,1)</m>, <m>f'(x) &lt; 0</m> on <m>(-2,1)</m> and <m>f'(x)</m> is constant on <m>(3,5)</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
      </task>
  </activity>
    
      <activity xml:id="activity-derivative-derivativetests3">
    <introduction>
      <p>
       Look back at the graph you made for <xref ref="activity-derivative-derivativetests2"/>.  
      </p>
    </introduction>
      <task>
      <statement>
          <p>Which of the following best describes what is occurring when graph changes from increasing to decreasing or decreasing to increasing?</p>
          <ol label="A">
              <li><p> There is a critical point.</p></li>
                <li><p> There is a relative maximum or minimum. </p></li>
                <li><p> The derivative might be undefined. </p></li>
                <li><p> The derivative might equal zero. </p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
      </task>
  </activity>
    
    <theorem xml:id="first-derivative-test"> <title>The First Derivative Test</title>  
      <introduction>
      <p>
       Suppose that <m>x=c</m> is a critical point of <m>f(x)</m> and that <m>f(x)</m> is continuous at <m>x=c</m>.   
      </p>
      </introduction>
    <p>
    <ol>   
    <li>If <m>f'(x) &gt; 0</m> to the left of <m>c</m> and <m>f'(x) &lt; 0</m> to the right of <m>c</m>, then a <b>relative maximum</b> occurs when <m>x=c</m>. </li>
    <li>If <m>f'(x) &lt; 0</m> to the left of <m>c</m> and <m>f'(x) &gt; 0 </m> to the right of <m>c</m>, then a <b>relative minimum </b> occurs when <m>x=c</m>.</li>
    <li>If <m>f'(x)</m> is the same sign on both sices of <m>x=c</m>, then neither a relative maximum nor a relative minimum occur when <m>x=c</m>.</li>
     </ol> </p>
    </theorem>

    <activity xml:id="activity-derivitative-derivativetests4">
        <introduction>
            <p> Let <m>f(x)=x^4-4x^3+4x^2</m></p>
        </introduction>
        <task> 
            <p>Find all critical points of <m>f(x)</m>. Plot them on the same number line.</p>
        </task>
        <task> 
            <p>What intervals have been created by subdividing the number line at the critical points?</p>
        </task>
        <task> 
            <p>Pick an <m>x</m>-value that lies in each interval. Determine whether <m>f'(x)</m> is positive or negative at each point.</p>
        </task>
        <task> 
            <p>On which intervals is <m>f(x)</m> increasing? On which intervals is <m>f(x)</m> decreasing?</p>
        </task>
        <task> 
            <p>List all relative maxima and relative minima.</p>
        </task>
    </activity>
    
    <remark> <title>Dealing with discontinuities</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>Our previous activity dealt with a function that was continuous for all real numbers. Because of that, we could trust our chart to point out relative extrema. Let's now consider what might happen if a function has any discontinuities.</p>
            <p> Draw a function that is increasing on the left of <m>x=1</m>, discontinuous at <m>x=1, </m><m>f(1)=\lim_{x \to 1^-}f(x)</m>, and decreasing to the right of <m>x=1</m>. Does the derivative of <m>f(x)</m> exist at <m>x=1</m>?  Does your graph have a local maximum or minimum at <m>x=1</m>?</p>
        </introduction>
    </remark>
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-derivative-derviativetest5">
        <introduction>
            <p>Let <m>f(x)=\frac{x}{(x-2)^2}</m>.</p>
            <p>Note that <m>f(x)</m> is not defined for <m>x=2</m>. So <m>x=2</m> cannot be a critical point and thus cannot be the location of a relative extrema. However, the function may be increasing on one side of <m>x=2</m> and decreasing on the other, so we must still include it on our number line.</p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <p> Find all critical points of <m>f(x)</m>. Plot them and any discontinuities for <m>f(x)</m> on the same number line.</p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p> What intervals have been created by subdividing the number line at the critical points and discontinuities?</p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p> Pick an <m>x</m>-value that lies in each interval. Determine whether <m>f'(x)</m> is positive or negative each point.</p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p> On which intervals is <m>f(x)</m> increasing? On which intervals is <m>f(x)</m> decreasing?</p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p> List all relative maxima and relative minima. </p>
        </task>
    </activity>
    
    <activity xml:id="activity-derivative-derivativetest6">
        <introduction>
            <p>For each of the following functions, find the intervals on which <m>f(x)</m> is increasing or decreasing. Then identify any relative extrema.</p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <p><m>f(x)=x^3+3x^2+3x+1</m></p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p><m>f(x)=\frac{1}{2}x+\cos x</m> on <m>(0,2\pi)</m></p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p><m>f(x)=(x^2-9)^{2/3}</m></p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p><m>f(x)= \ln(2x-1)</m>. (Hint: think about the domain of this one before you get started!)</p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p><m>f(x)=\frac{x^2}{x^2-4}</m></p>
        </task>
    </activity>
